Abstract

With the increase in the generation and spread of textual content on social media, natural language processing (NLP) has become an important area of research for detecting underlying threats, racial abuse, violence, and implied warnings in the content. The subtlety and ambiguity of language make the development of effective models for detecting threats in text a challenging task. This task is further complicated when the threat is not explicitly conveyed. This study focuses on the task of implied threat detection using an explicitly designed machine-generated dataset with both linguistic and lexical features. We evaluated the performance of different machine learning algorithms on these features including Support Vector Machines, Logistic Regression, Naive Bayes, Decision Tree, and K-nearest neighbors. The ensembling approaches of Adaboost, Random Forest, and Gradient Boosting were also explored. Deep learning modeling was performed using Long Short-Term Memory, Deep Neural Networks (DNN), and Bidirectional Long Short-Term Memory (BiLSTM). Based on the evaluation, it was observed that classical and ensemble models overfit while working with linguistic features. The performance of these models improved when working with lexical features. The model based on logistic regression exhibited superior performance with an F1 score of 77.13%. While experimenting with deep learning models, DNN achieved an F1 score of 91.49% while the BiLSTM achieved an F1 score of 91.61% while working with lexical features. The current study provides a baseline for future research in the domain of implied threat detection.

1 Introduction

The widespread use and popularity of social media has made it easier than ever for individuals to connect with each other [1]. Due to the use of emojis, memes, unclear phrasing, improper syntax, broken grammar, abbreviations, and incomplete sentences, the language used on social media greatly differs from the language used in face-to-face interactions [2]. While this has increased the ability to interact and exchange information, a considerably large number of users on social media today communicate using inappropriate, impolite, disrespectful, hostile, or downright abusive language [3]. The term abusive language was, among others, coined by Niemann et al. to refer to statements that include hurtful, derogatory, or obscene utterances made by one person to another person [4]. These statements can also include swearing, name-calling, or the use of profanity [5]. Due to the anonymity offered in the online world, people often indulge in the use of speech that would be considered crude or vile in offline, face-to-face interactions [6]. This form of communication generates new challenges such as identifying online abuse [2, 3], cyber-bullying [7, 8], hate speech [9, 10], and online threats [11, 12]. With the increased growth of Machine Learning (ML) and Natural Language Processing (NLP), researchers started exploring these techniques and methods for detecting abusive language being used in online interactions [2].

Much like online abuse, online threat detection is an emerging and challenging issue. A threat can be defined as the intent to cause harm or damage. The task of online threat detection is defined as “the process of detecting text that is intended to threaten an entity (Human, Organization, or Country) of harmful consequences” [13]. Sentences 1 and 2 are examples of threatening language.

  1. (1)

    I will kill you.

  2. (2)

    They will blow up the gas pipeline.

Similar to online abuse, online threats can be categorized into two types: direct threats and indirect, implicit, or implied threats. A direct threat contains explicit words such as Kill, Bomb, Hurt, Murder, Annihilate, and Destroy, that definitively point towards some threatening situation. An implied threat points towards a threatening situation in a subtle manner; the threat is not directly stated but rather vaguely implied. The sentiment behind the threat is not conveyed by threatening words. Sentences 3, 4, 5, and 6 are examples of implied threats. Sentence 3 implies that a person needs to be careful while chasing some goal or ambition. It specifically reflects a warning against harm that may befall the individual due to arrogance or self-importance due to an increase in social status or popularity. Sentence 4 implies that the person is undertaking something that could lead to dangerous or catastrophic consequences. It can be construed as a warning against the provocation of a negative outcome. Sentence 5 is a veiled threat. There is a strong implication in the sentence that damage will be inflicted on the car if certain conditions are not met. In sentence 6, the cost of disappointment may not be monetary at all. This sentence implies that the intended person will not be able to handle the retaliation, harm, or consequences that would follow should they not complete some task that has been assigned to them.

  1. (3)

    Don’t fly so high or your wings might melt.

  2. (4)

    Wonder if you’d still play with fire so much if you got burned.

  3. (5)

    You have a beautiful car. It would be a shame if anything were to happen to it.

  4. (6)

    You won’t be able to bear the cost of disappointing me.

It is important to understand that analyzing text with words such as ruin, hurt, harm, kill, or destroy can be linked to threats, as these words explicitly imply damage. Sentences with such words are easier to identify due to the presence of hateful words. However, taking an example of the sentence: It would be a shame if something happened to you or I hope you get what you deserve; the words that make up these sentences will not be considered overtly threatening. The extraction of sentences where threats are implied is a daunting task and makes the analysis task even more challenging [14]. Another major issue in dealing with this kind of content on social media is the rate at which this content is generated and the sheer size of the content across online platforms [15]. Due to the volume and velocity of the web content being generated by millions of users, it is humanly impossible to monitor all this data [16]. There is, thus, a need for a mechanism that can automate the human review effort toward the most needed content. In recent years, there has been significant progress in the field of ML and NLP, with new techniques and algorithms being developed that are specifically designed for analyzing textual data [17]. Researchers have actively started exploring these techniques and methods for detecting abusive language being used in online interactions.

It is important to note that the integration of NLP and ML does not just have the potential to improve text classification but it can also facilitate nuanced predictions. ML techniques have permitted the creation of sophisticated algorithms aimed at textual data analysis of emails, social media posts, documents, and website content. However, an increase in the size of textual data being processed exponentially raises the complexity of the level of analysis needed. This is a considerable challenge for typical ML methodologies, prompting the investigation of more advanced techniques such as deep learning. Deep learning is a type of machine learning that is inspired by the design and operation of the human brain's neural nets. Deep learning has emerged as a potential approach to addressing the complexities of text-mining tasks. Recently, deep learning has emerged as the most popular method for text analysis because of advancements such as transformer architecture [18], transfer learning [19], and Large Language Model (LLMs) [20]. These breakthroughs have transformed jobs like sentiment analysis, text categorization [21], and hate speech identification [19].

The aims of this study are twofold: (1) generating a synthetic dataset containing implied threats, and (2) demonstrating the detection of implied threats with the help of machine learning, ensemble methods, and deep learning. Especially, the key objectives and major contributions are reported as follows:

  1. 1.

    In the absence of datasets pertaining to implied or indirect threats, a machine-generated dataset has been compiled exclusively for this research. This choice was necessary since existing datasets do not contain the necessary data needed to detect implied threats in textual content. The dataset was generated using a Large Language Model (LLM) and human in-loop technique. It contains linguistic and textual features. The dataset was also annotated using LLM and validated through human reviewers.

  2. 2.

    After performing linguistic analysis on the generated dataset, data modeling was carried out using classical ML models, ensemble ML models, and deep learning models. The feature-weighing approach used in data modeling was TF-IDF.

  3. 3.

    We have benchmarked our results on the task of ITD using Precision, Accuracy, Recall, F1 Score, and Area Under the Curve of the Receiver Operating Characteristic curve (AUC ROC).

The rest of the paper is organized as follows: Sect. 2 shows the related work and gap analysis for ITD. Section 3 outlines the research methodology for the paper discussing the data generation and the properties of the dataset suitable for this task. The section also explores the linguistic features present in the data in addition to discussing the ML and deep learning modeling methodology applied in this study. Section 4 presents the results of the experiments including a discussion on the errors in the prediction and the rationale behind those errors and predictions. Section 6 presents the conclusion of this study.

2 Related Work

Recent years have seen a rise in analysis of textual content over social media. As this platform comprises of individuals across the globe sharing and commenting on issues close to their hearts in terms of beliefs, principles, religion, and ethnicity, a difference of opinion often gives rise to hate and abuse. Hate speech on social media can be observed in different forms such as abusive language [22, 23], offensive language [24, 25], cyber-bullying [8], and use of threatening language [26]. The data are generated every second by millions of users across the globe, making the manual detection of hate speech next to impossible [16, 27]. To automate this process, ML, NLP, and deep learning are actively being used.

Initially, automatic hate speech detection techniques were based on lexicon [28, 29]. ML algorithms such as Support Vector Machines (SVM), Logistic regression, and naïve Bayes (NB) were frequently used for the classification of text into hate speech [30,31,32]. Modern deep learning architectures ranging from Recurrent Neural Networks (RNNs) to transformers have since also been applied for the prediction of hate speech [33, 34]. Sigurbergsson and Derczynski explored 3600 Danish text comments obtained from Twitter, Facebook, and Reddit to classify text into the offensive and not-offensive class. The authors compared the performance of traditional ML with deep learning approaches and found the performance of deep learning approaches to be better than classical ML [35]. Akhter et al. used comments from YouTube and classified them into abusive and not-abusive classes [36]. The authors compared the performance of ML models including SVM, NB, and K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN), with deep learning models including CNN and LSTM. Deep learning models were found more efficient at detecting abusive language. Ashraf et al. also used comments from YouTube and classified them as abusive or not abusive [37]. Feature extraction using TF-IDF and n-grams were explored in the research. They compare the performance of eight ML classifiers including SVM, NB, and DT with two deep learning models based on 1-Dimensional CNN and LSTM. The model based on 1-Dimensional CNN outperformed the remaining models in the detection of abusive comments.

Collecting data from social media platforms of Facebook and Twitter along with data from Bengali newspapers, Wadud et al. explored the use of classical ML, ensemble, and deep learning approaches to categorize offensive and non-offensive textual content [38]. The analysis focused on the detection of direct or explicitly offensive language. The performance of the generated models was evaluated using the metrics of accuracy, precision, and recall. The authors concluded that their proposed LSTM-Boost approach achieved better performance in classifying offensive content. Haq et al. address the issue of direct offensive content detection in Pushto [39]. Using tweets, the authors compiled a dataset for the detection of directly offensive and non-offensive textual content. Their experiments investigated the effectiveness of deep learning models and transfer learning techniques for detecting explicitly offensive textual content. The research focused on the use of CNN, RNN, LSTM, and Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers (BERT). The research uncovered that BERT and LSTM outperform in the detection of explicitly offensive content.

Ocampo et al. provide a detailed analysis of seven benchmarked datasets for hate-speech detection [14]. Their research makes use of neural network architectures and concludes that although these models can efficiently detect explicit hate speech, they perform poorly when tasked to detect implied hate speech. One of the key research areas within the domain of hate speech detection is the identification of threatening language on social media or over online platforms using NLP and ML [23, 24] which, although challenging, is extremely important, as the results impact individuals, groups, and governments. Researchers have employed various approaches to study the automatic identification of threatening language in heterogeneous datasets. Chakraborty and Seddiqui have performed the classification of tweets into the classes of threat and no-threat in the Bengali language using SVM, NB, Convolutional Neural Network (CNN), and Long short-term model (LSTM) [40]. Amjad et al. use ML algorithms such as SVM and deep learning algorithms like LSTM for threat detection in Urdu [41].

Datasets used for modeling vary from study to study. Table 1 shows some datasets used for the detection of explicitly threatening language. A constraint on these datasets is that they were compiled by extracting content from social media using offensive keywords. This method of extracting content limits the inclusion of implied threat content which lacks overtly threatening words. All of the datasets belong to the classification category; classes of the dataset are diverse, and both binary and multi-class datasets is presented in Table 1. These datasets are inclusive in terms of languages as Table 1 contains datasets from English, Chinese, and Urdu. These datasets were collected from popular social media site Twitter, and annotated through humans. The use of these datasets results in limited size and variety of data.

2.1 Gap Analysis

Based on a review of the related work and dataset analysis presented in Table 1, it can be observed that although there are studies available on the subject of hate, abusive, or offensive speech detection, fewer studies focus on threat detection. Furthermore, exploring research with the aim of detecting threatening language, we can see several multi-lingual models are being created but these studies focus on the detection of direct or explicit threats without tackling the problem of implied threats or detection of threats made in a manner that does not always come across as threatening. None of the studies in the explored literature targeted indirect threat detection in the domain of hate speech prediction.

The closest study to our research targeted the issue of implicit abuse detection [5]. In the study by Wiegand et al. [5] and Wiegand et al. [48], researchers used ML models to detect indirect or implicit abuse in text. Taking inspiration from Wiegand et al. [5], the focus of this study is on the detection of implied threats. It needs to be noted that compiling a dataset by extracting content from social media using offensive keywords would not only be time-consuming but also limit the inclusion of implied threat content as such text would lack overtly threatening words. As the studies by Hartvigsen et al. and Das et al. have shown the potential validity of using machine-generated datasets [49, 50], we propose a machine-generated dataset for ITD in the current study. Using prompt engineering, we demonstrate the use of the LLM ChatGPT to generate implied threat sentences. We attempt to improve the accuracy of the generated dataset by using the human-in-loop approach [51]. We apply ML and deep learning modeling to the dataset using lexical and linguistic features. We also explore the limitations and strengths of automating the process of ITD. We recognize that using the LLM ChatGPT for generating the dataset will unavoidably result in artificial data. However, this was the only way of compiling an unbiased dataset of sufficient size to research this topic.

3 Methodology

The research methodology flowchart is represented in Fig. 1 comprising five blocks, namely, 1) Dataset Generation and Validation, 2) Data Preprocessing and Exploration, 3) Feature Engineering, 4) Data Modeling, and 5) Model Evaluation.

3.1 Dataset Generation and Validation

As the focus of this study was to perform ITD, we have proposed a dataset of our own since there were no publicly available datasets for undertaking this task. The dataset was generated using LLM and human in-loop technique. The LLM used for generating the dataset was ChatGPT. A set of prompts was given to ChatGPT, and the mapping of the generated data and the prompt was then confirmed by humans. If the generated sentences did not match the prompt, the prompt was revised. The goal of this process was to obtain high-quality sentences which were then made a part of the dataset.

3.1.1 Prompt Engineering

Prompt: A prompt in the context of language models refers to the input or query provided to the model to generate a response. When one interacts with a chatbot interface such as ChatGPT, one typically starts by entering a prompt, which can be a question, statement, or any text that conveys their request or intent. Prompt in the context of this study is the text used to generate sentences depicting implicit threats.

Prompt Design: We have used a specifically crafted prompt to generate the dataset for this study. There are two types of sentences present in the dataset. First, sentences that convey indirect or implied threats without the use of any explicitly threatening words. These sentences portray a warning or an implied future consequence that is subtle in nature. The obvious meaning of the statement and the underlying meaning are different. Second, sentences that do not represent a threat (direct or implied) but mean something other than what is written. Thus, two types of prompts were used: one for the implied threat class and one for the non-threat class. The following is an example of the prompt used to generate indirect or implied threat sentences: Generate 50 implied threat sentences, and also show who is the target and the actor in these sentences. The target is the one against whom the threat is being made and the actor is the one making the threat.

Prompt Optimization: The number 50 was chosen after a process of trial and error as 100 was too big of a response to be generated by ChatGPT and for 20 or 30 it would take more time to generate an ample-sized dataset. This process was repeated numerous times as often the same response would be given. The prompt was then updated with the statement Do not repeat previous sentences. All the sentences generated as a result of this process were labeled ‘threat’. The same process was repeated for non-threat sentences with the prompt: Generate 50 implied sentences that say one thing but mean something else. All these sentences were labeled as non-threat. The extent to which these labels were correct is discussed in the upcoming section.

3.1.2 Data Annotation

In this study, data annotation was performed using LLM (ChatGPT). The data generated from the prompt was labeled based on the prompt text for example if the prompt text was “Generate 50 implied threat sentences” all those generated sentences were labeled as a threat and if the prompt said “Generate 50 implied sentences” those sentences were labeled as no-threat. Other features such as actor and target were also labeled by the model while generating these sentences. Lastly, the polarity of these sentences was calculated using Textblob, a popular NLP toolkit used for sentiment analysis. Automated annotation is the key feature of this dataset as this provides the ability to generate large datasets for low-resource tasks. The task of implied threat detection was considered challenging because of the lack of data so this methodology allowed us to generate data for this task. The validity of the dataset was ensured using human validation.

3.1.3 Human Validation

A human validation approach was used to confirm the accuracy of the generated dataset. Five human validators, three men and two women, who were proficient in speaking and understanding English participated in the validation process. Each validator received a sample of 100 randomly selected sentences from the created dataset, and they were instructed to annotate the sentences according to their opinion on the presence of an underlying threat in the sentences. Inter-annotator agreement measures were computed to evaluate the consensus among the human validators as well as actual labels. The evaluating agreement was based on the measure of Cohen’s Kappa.

Table 2 represents a matrix of agreement scores, specifically Cohen’s Kappa scores, between human annotators and the actual label AL. Each row and column corresponds to an annotator (A1, A2, A3, A4, A5) and the actual label (AL), respectively. Cohen’s Kappa is a metric of inter-annotator agreement, and the scores in Table 2 show the level of agreement between each annotator and the true label. The values range from 0 to 1, where 0 indicates agreement is no better than chance, and 1 represents perfect agreement.

The intersection of row A1 and column A3 contains a value of 0.657. This means that annotator A1 has a Cohen’s Kappa score of 0.657 when compared to the actual label AL. A higher Kappa score indicates a higher level of agreement between the annotator and the true label. Based on Table 2, it is found that some annotators show a higher level of agreement with the actual label (e.g., A1, A2, A3) than others (e.g., A4, A5). The values in the diagonal of the table (where the annotator is the same as the actual label) represent the agreement of each annotator with themselves, hence they are all equal to 1, as expected.

3.1.4 Generated Dataset

The dataset contains indirect or implied sentences i.e. sentences that say one thing but can be interpreted or inferred as something else such as sentences 7, 8, and 9.

  1. (7)

    You’re on thin ice.

  2. (8)

    It would be unwise to ignore my request.

  3. (9)

    Time flies like an arrow.

The proposed dataset has binary classes: threat and no-threat. Threat class represents sentences that have an element of threat as depicted in sentences 7 and 8. A no-threat class contains the sentences which are also implied but they do not have an element of threat as depicted through sentence 9. The total size of the dataset was 2462 rows or sentences. The dataset has 6 fields: Sentence, Actual Meaning, Actor, Target, Polarity, and Class. Sentence is the piece of text for detection of Threat or No-threat, actual meaning shows the meaning of the sentence in its true sense, actor, target, and polarity are defined in the terminology Sect. 3.3.1, and class represents a threat and no-threat label. Table 3 shows a sample of the dataset with all the fields.

3.2 Data Preprocessing and Exploration

The first preprocessing transformation applied to the sentences identified under the threat class was to remove all punctuation and any special characters. Next, stopword removal was applied to eliminate high-frequency words that contribute very little to classification. This included words like “the”, “is”, “a”, “am”, and so on. Stemming was applied next to reduce words to their root form. Stemming helps reduce ambiguity and the number of features whilst improving the efficiency of the model. In addition to textual data, we have also preprocessed categorical data. Label encoder was applied to the class, actor, and target fields to convert textual categories in these fields to numerical ones. This involved assigning a unique numerical value to each label, which allowed the model to work with categorical data more effectively. As there was some repetition in the dataset for both classes: threat and no-threat, the repeating rows were deleted. After removing the recurring sentences, the actual size of the dataset was 1838 from which 1150 sentences belong to the threat class and 678 belong to the no-threat class. This acceptable imbalance in the dataset was retained to bring the generated dataset as close to a real-world scenario as possible. Another cleaning transformation that was applied to the dataset comprised of unifying the target and actor features of the dataset; all instances were lower capped. Thus, Rogue element and rogue Element became uniform. An example depicting the preprocessing carried out is outlined in Fig. 2.

3.2.1 Data Exploration

In exploratory data analysis, sentence, target, actor, and class fields were analyzed. Table 4 shows the dataset statistics in terms of the number of instances of classes we have before and after cleaning. The number of unique actors and targets in the dataset has also been computed. It is important to note that the unique actor and target values belong to the threat class as target and actor are not available for the no-threat class and have been represented as na in the dataset.

Sentence features were explored and analyzed using n-gram analysis, with a focus on identifying the frequency and distribution of uni-, bi-, and trigrams for the classes: threat and no-threat. The results of the analysis are summarized in Tables 4 and 5. Table 5 provides valuable insights into the language patterns and themes that are associated with the two classes, and can be used to infer further analysis and modeling of the text data. Table 6 shows the five most common actors and target of threats.

3.3 Feature Engineering

3.3.1 Linguistic Features

This study consists of different linguistic features used for supervised classification. All these features are automatically generated during the process of dataset creation. These features individually and collectively play a vital role in ITD.

Actor: An actor can be regarded as the perpetrator; an entity making the threat or intending to cause harm. This entity is sometimes present in the sentence and sometimes not, as can be observed in sentences 10 and 11. Sentence 10 exhibits threatening language but the actor is not a part of the sentence. A potential actor in sentence 10 could be an interrogator, insinuator, or even a mobster, and for sentence 11, a hacker, cybersecurity expert, or whistleblower. The feature “actor” can be a key factor in predicting if a sentence is threatening or not. Extracting this feature manually was a challenging task that was achieved during the process of dataset creation using LLMs that generated sentences as well as features (Actor, Target) automatically with the help of prompts.

  1. (10)

    I have ways of making you talk.

  2. (11)

    You’re not as anonymous as you think.

Target: This is the entity being subjected to the threat. In the case of ITD, the target may not always be a part of the sentence; even if the target is a part of the sentence, the representation may not always be direct as observed in sentence 12. This feature can also help in making better predictions.

  1. (12)

    You don’t want to find out what will happen if you don’t pay on time.

Polarity: Polarity is a sentiment score for the text. Its value lies between –1 and 1. 0 means a neutral sentiment, a value of 1 or closer to 1 depicts a positive sentiment and a value closer to –1 depicts a negative sentiment. Usually sentiment of threatening sentences is negative so this type of score is an important feature for ITD.

3.3.2 Lexical Features Extraction

For ML and ensemble ML models, the term Frequency Inverse Document Frequency (TF- IDF) was used for feature extraction. TF-IDF is the statistical measure of the importance of a word in a corpus. The main concept behind TF-IDF is that words that appear more frequently in a document but less frequently in the corpus are more important and should have higher scores. To calculate the TF-IDF score for a term in a document Eq. 1 was used.

tfidfi,j=tfidfi,j∗logNdfi
(1)

In Eq. 1tfi,j is the number of times a word “i” occurs in documents “j”, and dfi is the number of documents with the word “i”. “N” is the total number of documents. Example of using TF-IDF vectorization on a set of sentences: S1: “If you knew what was better for you, you’d be more careful of your words.”, S2: “I hope you don’t regret your decision.” S3: “We wouldn’t want anything to happen to those who aren’t being careful.” S4: “It’s important to consider all of the potential risks before making a choice.” S5: “It’s interesting how some people don’t seem to care about the consequences of their actions.”

For deep learning models, Tokenized, padded, and encoded sequence representation was used. This representation was achieved with the combination of three steps: Tokenization, Padding, and Encoding. Tokenization is the process of breaking down a piece of text into smaller units [52]. This step involves splitting the text into individual tokens. For this study, sentences were broken into tokens of words. For example, the sentence “Threat detection is an important NLP task” can be tokenized into [“Threat”, “detection”, “is”, “an”, “important” “NLP”, “task”]. The input text sentences are of variable length but the neural networks require fixed-length input. Padding was used to resolve this issue. In padding shorter sequences are padded with special tokens (usually 0 s) to match the length of the longest sequence in the dataset. Padding makes sure that all sequences have the same length. For example, if the maximum sequence length in a dataset is 10, and the input sequence is [“Thats”, “Great”], we can pad it with 0 s to get [0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, “Thats”, “Great”, 0, 0]. Table 7 reports TF-IDF vectorization for the sentences S1, S2, S3, S4, and S5.

Deep learning models cannot directly process text data, so there is a need to convert each token in the padded sequence into a numerical representation. One common method is to use an embedding layer that maps each token to a dense vector of fixed size. For example, the word “that” can be mapped to the vector [0.2, 0.5, 0.1, 0.8, 0.4]. After encoding, each sequence of tokens becomes a sequence of dense vectors.

3.4 Data Modeling

After completing the data exploration and analysis phase, the next step was to build a predictive model that could classify new text data into the threat or no-threat class. Three categories of models were used in this paper: classical, ensemble ML, and deep learning. This section provides a comprehensive overview of the data modeling process.

3.4.1 Classical Machine Learning Models

Classical ML models are statistical models that learn patterns and relationships in data to make predictions or decisions. These models are typically based on a set of features or variables that are used to train the model [53]. Classical ML models have been widely used in a variety of applications, including image recognition, speech recognition, NLP, and recommendation systems. These models are often computationally efficient and can be trained on relatively small datasets. When dealing with complex and high-dimensional data, classical ML models are not as effective as deep learning Models. The following are the classical ML models used in this study: SVM, Logistic Regression, NB, Decision Tree, and KNN.

Logistic regression performs binary classification by fitting a logistic function for a multi-class; in the case of binary classification, each label is divided into a yes or no class [54]. SVM identifies a hyperplane that differentiates the data into distinct classes [55]. Decision trees use a set of rules to create a tree-like structure to classify data [56]. NB is a probabilistic model that calculates the probability of each class depending on the probability of each feature [57]. KNN classifies data depending on the label of its K nearest neighbor in the feature space [58].

3.4.2 Ensemble Machine Learning Models

In Ensemble Machine Learning model predictions of several base models are combined for better performance [59]. Ensemble ML models are used in a variety of scenarios such as image classification, speech recognition, and NLP [60]. Ensemble models are usually more computationally expensive and hard to interpret compared to individual models. Following are the models we have used in this study: Adaboost, Random Forest, and Gradient Boosting.

A random forest comprises of several decision trees, in a random forest each tree is trained on a random subset of data and features. The final prediction is made by combining the predictions of the individual trees [61]. Adaboost is a boosting ensemble algorithm. It combines the weak classifiers to create a strong classifier by assigning weights to miss-classified predictions. Gradient Boosting is also a boosting algorithm. It is trained on a series of models where each model is made to learn from the errors of the previous model. Gradient Boosting minimizes a loss by updating the model parameters towards obtaining a negative gradient of the loss function [62].

3.4.3 Deep Learning Models

Classical ML depends on feature selection methods of information gain, entropy, and several others to effectively build their models. These models tend to suffer while working on textual content as there is no universal feature selection method that works effectively across all ML models [38]. Deep learning is a branch of ML. It is based on artificial neural networks (ANN). These models are independent of explicit feature selection methods, a task that is automatically undertaken by the hidden layers within the network. As these models are robust at handling a high-dimensional feature space and long-term dependencies, these models have been used in different applications including text classification tasks [63]. The only concern while working with these models is that they are black-box models; the resultant model is not human interpretable, thus, it is not known which features are chosen for the analysis. Deep learning models have achieved state-of-the-art benchmarking performance on different datasets. The deep learning models discussed in this study are LSTM, Deep Neural Network (DNN), and Bidirectional Long Short-Term Memory (BiLSTM) as these models are well-equipped to handle semantic information from text for improved classification.

DNN is used for text classification in this study by taking in an encoded sequence of words as input and passing it through dense layers. The last layer is a softmax layer that generates a probability distribution over the potential classes. LSTM is a type of RNN. These models are used for processing sequential data [64]. LSTM uses an encoded sequence of words as an input and then it passes through a series of LSTM cells. The final classification is produced by passing it through a dense layer. BiLSTM is an improved version of LSTM. BiLSTM processes data in both backward and forward directions; it allows the model to get both future and past context.

3.5 Model Evaluation

ML models are evaluated based on certain evaluation metrics. The following evaluation metrics were used to assess the performance of the ML models generated in this study: Precision, Accuracy, Recall, F1 Score, and Area Under the Curve of the Receiver Operating Characteristic curve (AUC ROC).

Accuracy measures the proportion of correct predictions that the model makes out of all the predictions it makes [65]. It is calculated as the number of correct predictions divided by the total number of predictions as shown by Eq. 2. Precision measures the proportion of true positives (correctly identified positives) out of all the positive predictions that the model makes [66]. It is calculated as the number of true positives divided by the sum of true positives and false positives and represented by Eq. 3.

Recall measures the proportion of true positives out of all the actual positives in the data [66]. It is calculated as the number of true positives divided by the sum of true positives and false negatives. It is mathematically represented by Eq. 4. F1 score is the harmonic mean of precision and recall and provides a balanced measure of the two. F1 score can be calculated as shown by Eq. 5. The AUC ROC measures the performance of a binary classification model at different classification thresholds. It plots the true positive rate (recall) against the false positive rate (1-specificity) for different threshold values. The area under the ROC curve (AUC) provides a measure of how well the model is able to distinguish between positive and negative examples [67].

4 Experimental Results

In this study, we utilized an 80–20 data split to train and evaluate our ML model. This means that 80% of the dataset was used for training the model, while the remaining 20% was reserved for validation purposes. This split ensured that the model was trained on a substantial portion of the data while also allowing us to assess its performance on unseen data, which helps gauge its generalization capabilities. To carry out the experiments and model training, we leveraged the computational resources provided by Google Colab. Google Colab was configured to include 128 GB of storage and 16 GB of RAM, ensuring that necessary computational capacity was available to handle our data and ML tasks efficiently.

4.1 Linguistic Features

The performance of classic and ensemble ML algorithms was first evaluated on linguistic features. Table 8 presents the statistics for the observed results.

Among classical ML algorithms, SVM emerged as the better performing algorithm, achieving a 97.47% F1-score on linguistic features. Decision tree, NB, and KNN achieved 100% precision, recall, and F1-score on linguistic features. Models with 100% accuracy, precision, recall, or F1 score suggest that these models are overfitting the training data. In other words, the model fits the training data so well that it is not able to generalize to new, unseen data. This can be occurring as the target and actor linguistic features are very distinct for threat and no-threat classes; there is no overlapping of actor and target features for both classes. Logistic regression underfitted on linguistic features with low evaluation scores.

Among ensemble ML algorithms, Random Forest, Adaboost, and Gradient Boosting achieved 100% precision, recall, and F1-score on linguistic features. While working with linguistic features, we can observe that these models overgeneralize because of disjoint values in features like actor and target for both classes. To better understand algorithm behavior, the ROC curve was plotted for all the algorithms for the linguistic feature set (see Fig. 3). The results from Table 8 support the observations from the ROC curve in Fig. 3. We can observe that models with linguistic features are overgeneralizing on the dataset. The confusion matrix for the algorithms is presented in Fig. 4.

4.2 Lexical Features—TF-IDF

Observing the results for TF-IDF in Table 9, classical models are not over-generalizing, underscoring their use as a better feature set for prediction. The best-performing model using these features was the model generated by logistic regression with an F1 score of 77.13%, followed by SVM and KNN with an F1 score of 76.48% and 74.96%, respectively. NB showed the least favorable results with an F1 score of 31.1%. The performance of the ensemble learning algorithms on TF-IDF features was reasonably good, with F1-scores ranging from 71.3 to 75.4%. The same can be observed in the ROC curve for classical and ensemble ML on TF-IDF (see Fig. 3).

4.3 Linguistic + Lexical Features (TF-IDF)

With a combination of both features, the best performing model was the SVM with an F1 score of 94.84%, followed by KNN with an F1 score of 92.18% (see Table 10). With the presence of linguistic features both NB and decision tree over generalized for the same reason as the models with only linguistic features. Among ensemble ML algorithms, Random Forest, Adaboost, and Gradient Boosting have achieved 100% precision, recall, and F1-score on a combination of linguistic features and TF-IDF features. For a combination of linguistic and TF-IDF features, these models overgeneralize because of disjoint values in features like actor and target for both classes. The ROC curve for classical and ensemble ML on a combination of LF and TF-IDF is depicted in Fig. 3, whereas the confusion matrix for the algorithms is presented in Fig. 4.

4.4 Encoded Vectors

As linguistic features tend to overgeneralize with classical and ensemble algorithms, they have not been used while experimenting with deep learning models. As seen in Table 11, only textual features, in the form of encoded vectors, were used in the deep learning models.

Among deep learning algorithms, DNN and BiLSTM have achieved good performance with F1-scores of 91.49% and 91.61%, respectively. LSTM had an F1-score of 77.54% which was lower compared to the other algorithms. The results clearly show that the deep learning algorithms outperformed all other algorithms without over-generalizing.

By analyzing the true positive, true negative, false positive, and false negatives for the ML model and ensemble model for the TF-IDF feature, it was evident these types of models were not good at predicting positive cases i.e. threat class. The values of true positive and false positive were lower throughout the evaluation for TF-IDF cases (see Fig. 4).

To make the model better at predicting threat and no-threat from implicit text it is important to understand the words that are playing a role in the prediction. Table 12 shows the important words in the form of unigram, bigram, and trigram that contribute the most to the prediction of the class. It can be seen from the table that words like “want”, “would”, “might”, and “think” are commonly used in the “Threat Class” section to indicate uncertainty or speculative phrasing. Bigrams and trigrams like “might want”, “shame something happen”, and “anything bad happen” indicate hesitation or contemplation in potentially dangerous circumstances. In contrast, the “No-Threat Class” portion includes terms such as “I'm”, “sure”, and “really” which communicate confidence or assurance. Bigrams and trigrams such as “I'm sure”, “I'm really”, and “I'm certain I'm” strengthen this emotion by conveying certainty or conviction in non-threatening situations.

4.5 Comparative analysis

For classical ML while considering TF-IDF, the generated models by LR, SVM, Decision Tree, NB, and KNN exhibit underfitting, indicating that they struggle to capture the complexities of the data. However, when additional features are considered (LF + TF-IDF), SVM and KNN demonstrate the best fit, while DT and NB overfit. In terms of Ensemble ML models like Random Forest, AdaBoost, and Gradient Boosting exhibit underfitting when using TF-IDF features. However, when incorporating additional features (LF + TF-IDF), they tend to overfit, suggesting a more complex relationship between features. Deep learning models such as DNNEMB and BiLSTMEMB demonstrate the best fitting performance, suggesting they effectively capture the underlying patterns in the data. In contrast, LSTMEMB appears to underfit, implying a potential need for a more complex architecture.

5 Limitations

The following are the limitations of this study: first, the linguistic features used in the dataset tend to over-generalize the classes, making it challenging for the model to differentiate the threat and no-threat classes. Secondly, implied speech varies from language to language due to different morphological and syntactical structures, so implied threat detection varies from language to language. As this study is limited to English, due to well-known anatomy and easy-to-access tools for analysis, this study cannot be generalized to other languages. Additionally, this study shows the model’s bias toward the negative class, which can lead to poor performance in the prediction of positive cases.

6 Conclusion and Future Work

This study focuses on the task of ITD. Due to the unavailability of any publicly available dataset, we created a machine-generated binary classification dataset for the purpose of this research. The dataset contained both textual and linguistic features. We evaluated the performance of classical ML, ensemble, and deep learning algorithms on different sets of features. Based on the evaluation, it was observed that classical and ensemble ML algorithms tend to overfit while working with linguistic features. The performance of classical and ensemble ML algorithms improved when working with textual features. The model based on logistic regression exhibited superior performance with an F1 score of 77.13%. While experimenting with deep learning models, the DNN achieved an F1 score of 91.49% while the BiLSTM achieved an F1 score of 91.61% while working with textual features.

The main limitation of the dataset arises due to the linguistic features which seem to make the models over-generalize based on the class distribution. For the textual features, models tend to be biased towards the negative class. This could be due to similarity in statements as the sentences had an element of implied threats and did not contain any explicit wording that could be used to differentiate between no-threat and implied threat. Model interpretability is also one of the limitations of this study.

For future work, this dataset would be provided to human annotators to gain better linguistic features that would be a representation of text but would not over-generalize. Also, more positive cases would be added to remove the bias towards the negative class. After doing this models from this study and more sophisticated models will be trained and a comparative analysis with the current study will be made. Model interpretability will also be researched as with interpretability we will be able to look inside the model to see what features have maximum impact and how model performance can be improved by understanding those features.
